medical thought. The chapters contain a wide range of sources presenting different perspectives rooted in distinct times and places, including translations of published and unpublished documents and transcripts of ethnographic interviews as well as accounts by missionaries and colonial authorities and materials from the contemporary United States and United Kingdom. Together, these varied sources illustrate the many intersections of Buddhism and medicine in the past and how this nexus continues to be crucial in today’s global context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMedicinexReligious aspectsxBuddhismvSources. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / History.2bisacsh1 aArai, Paula K. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBahir, Cody R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBright, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapitanio, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheung, Kin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChilson, Clark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoderey, Céline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeane, Susannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubois, Thomas David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunter, Assunta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrwin, Anthony Lovenheim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJamyang, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoffe, Ben P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel